The South African Cities Network says the country’s major cities are ill-prepared to deal with the effect of harsh weather changes. JOHANNESBURG - The South African Cities Network says South Africa's major cities are "ill-prepared" to deal with the effect of harsh weather changes. READ: SA needs aggressive climate change awareness campaigns The Network says due to urbanisation, most poor residents live in poorly located areas and need to be resettled in higher lying areas. READ: Durban at risk of severe flooding by 2050 South African Cities Network's Project Manager, Liteboho Makhele said sustainability and climate change is not taken seriously, a silo approach to planning and underfunding has led to the current crisis. Makhele said an integrated approach to the problem of climate change is necessary to make a meaningful change.